            <h2><a href="/business/">Business Division</a></h2>
            <p>Family businesses take a variety of forms such as a sole proprietorship, corporation, LLC or partnership owned just by the parties or with other owners, or a professional business such as a medical, dental, law, psychological practice.</p>
            <a href="/business/" class="btn btn-default btn-yellow">read more</a></div>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-4">
          <div class="blk">
            <h2><a href="/family-residence/">Family Residence Division</a></h2>
            <p>Dividing the family home in a divorce case can be relatively simple, or it raises many difficult issues.  Whenever I need an example of a property division issue that arises in a divorce case, the family home can usually be used as an example.</p>
            <a href="/family-residence/" class="btn btn-default btn-yellow">read more</a></div>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-4">
          <div class="blk">
            <h2><a href="/pensions/">Pension Division</a></h2>
            <p>A pension plan may be the most valuable asset of the marital estate, even if the working spouse has not retired. Understanding the pension is important in both dividing the assets of the marriage and in determining child and spousal support.</p>
            <a href="/pensions/" class="btn btn-default btn-yellow">read more</a></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="row">
        <div class="col-md-4">
          <div class="blk">
            <h2><a href="/premarital/">Premarital Agreements</a></h2>
            <p>In general, a premarital agreement is a written contract between parties that defines what is community property and separate property in a marriage and often defines what the rights and obligations are between parties regarding spousal support or alimony.  The premarital agreement applies in divorce and at death.<</p>
            <a href="/premarital/" class="btn btn-default btn-yellow">read more</a></div>
